 in Ssra. <br>
<br>
Personally, I loved the move. Yes, I have a problem with quite a few of my guild members, and I don't know another few at all. But it doesn't really bother me. I mean, I was in a family guild for 1 year until it folded and turned into a beginning raid guild; which also folded. I had started to raid, and I realized that I really liked it. So, when the second guild folded; I wanted to join a raiding guild, preferably one at the high-end so I could finally kill the mobs that drop the stuff I drooled over when posted on Alla. <br>
<br>
Do whatever makes you happy. Just understand that in a large raiding guild; you will not have the same chemistry and bondage between peopel as a whole that you would see in a family guild. Depending on the type of person you are, you will butt heads with a few of them; and I doubt you will get along with everyone all the time. If this does not bother you; if you don't care about who they are as long as they both do their jobs on a raid; then this fact won't matter. Joining an uber guild will often isolate you from your friends, from others, and will likely change your out-look on EQ; but if this is what you want then more power to you.<br>
<br>
One thing about *class desireablility* for a guild is that is isn't as well-defined as people would think. Clerics are not always the top head honcho for the classes raid guilds recruit. You'd be suprized, but I would say, in certain cases, the latter may be a more fitting description of the *desired classes* in that order:<br>
<br>
1) Mage<br>
2) Cleric<br>
T-2) Bard<br>
4) Beastlord (if your guild doens't have one that is lvl 60 yet and active)<br>
5) Warrior (MT calibur)<br>
6) Wiz<br>
7) ranger/rogue/monk<br>
<br>
Now, obviously the only thing that really concerns us is that 5-spot (since I'm assuming you're applying under your warrior as main). As so many others have mentioned, few guilds will turn down a warrior that has all of his AA in-tact. THat said, there are a few things.<br>
<br>
First; despite what others may tell you, it is NOT bad to level intensely in Velks/FG. HOWEVER, the big thing to remember is that there is a world load of difference between tanking and velks tanking. You must remember that getting lvl 60 with 50 AA does not mean you know everything there is to know about warriors, nor that you already know what you need to about high-end tanking. If you realize this and learn the other things on your own, then it doesn't matter where you hunt. <br>
<br>
Second; raid and raid often. Make yourself a nuisance to the officers; send them tells, find out when raids are, and if you can get on them and such. Make sure that if you are on, and you have time to commit to a raid; then you are there.<br>
<br>
third; if you are tanking, remember this. For this raid, the clerics and the other healers/curers that are in charge of healing you are the ABSOLUTE WORST members of their class that exist in Norrath. They are horrible, terrible, and you trust them as far as you can throw 'em. And for all intensive purposes; when you are tanking; EXPECT to die, plan to die, hell, even prepare your tells to your rezzers/buffers. This way, you won't be pissed off when you die over and over; and when you miraculously manage to live, you'll be taht much happier.  <p><center><p><font size = 3 colo = "blue"><b>Wilhelmm D'Averam<br>Warlord of the Apocalypse</b></font></p></center>

